I can help you set up similar logging configuration in your Spring Boot application! Based on the image, I can see you're using Logback with a rolling file appender configuration. Here are the steps:

## Steps to Add Logging Configuration

### 1. **Add Logback Dependency** (if not already present)

Add to your `pom.xml`:
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-logging</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

### 2. **Create logback-spring.xml**

Create a file named `logback-spring.xml` in `src/main/resources/` directory:

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<configuration>
    
    <!-- Properties for log paths -->
    <springProperty scope="context" name="LOG_PATH" source="logging.path" defaultValue="/opt/apps/weblogs/rdh-workflow"/>
    <springProperty scope="context" name="LOG_FILE" source="logging.file" defaultValue="${LOG_PATH}/app.log"/>
    
    <!-- Include default Spring Boot logging configuration -->
    <include resource="org/springframework/boot/logging/logback/defaults.xml"/>
    <include resource="org/springframework/boot/logging/logback/file-appender.xml"/>
    
    <!-- Console Appender -->
    <appender name="CONSOLE" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
        <encoder>
            <pattern>%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS} [%thread] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n</pattern>
        </encoder>
    </appender>
    
    <!-- Rolling File Appender -->
    <appender name="FILE_LOGGER" class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.RollingFileAppender">
        <file>${LOG_PATH}/Rdh_Workflow_Services.log</file>
        
        <encoder>
            <pattern>%d{yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS} [%thread] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n</pattern>
        </encoder>
        
        <rollingPolicy class="ch.qos.logback.core.rolling.SizeAndTimeBasedRollingPolicy">
            <fileNamePattern>${LOG_PATH}/Rdh_Workflow_Services.%d{yyyy-MM-dd}.%i.log</fileNamePattern>
            <maxFileSize>100MB</maxFileSize>
            <maxHistory>10</maxHistory>
            <totalSizeCap>5GB</totalSizeCap>
            <cleanHistoryOnStart>true</cleanHistoryOnStart>
        </rollingPolicy>
    </appender>
    
    <!-- Async Appender for better performance -->
    <appender name="FILE_LOGGER_ASYNC" class="ch.qos.logback.classic.AsyncAppender">
        <appender-ref ref="FILE_LOGGER"/>
    </appender>
    
    <!-- Logger configuration -->
    <logger name="org.springframework.boot" level="WARN">
        <appender-ref ref="FILE_LOGGER_ASYNC"/>
    </logger>
    
    <!-- Root logger -->
    <root level="INFO">
        <appender-ref ref="CONSOLE"/>
        <appender-ref ref="FILE_LOGGER_ASYNC"/>
    </root>
    
</configuration>
```

### 3. **Update application.properties**

Add these properties to `src/main/resources/application.properties`:

```properties
# Logging configuration
logging.path=/opt/apps/weblogs/rdh-workflow
logging.file=${logging.path}/app.log

# Log levels
logging.level.root=INFO
logging.level.com.yourpackage=DEBUG
logging.level.org.springframework.web=WARN
```

### 4. **Create Log Directory**

Make sure the log directory exists and has write permissions:
```bash
sudo mkdir -p /opt/apps/weblogs/rdh-workflow
sudo chmod 755 /opt/apps/weblogs/rdh-workflow
```

### 5. **Use Logging in Your Code**

In your Java classes:
```java
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

public class YourService {
    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(YourService.class);
    
    public void someMethod() {
        logger.info("This is an info message");
        logger.debug("This is a debug message");
        logger.error("This is an error message", exception);
    }
}
```

### Key Features from the Configuration:

- **Rolling Policy**: Files rotate daily and when they reach 100MB
- **Max History**: Keeps last 10 log files
- **Total Size Cap**: Maximum 5GB of logs
- **Async Logging**: Better performance with AsyncAppender
- **Pattern**: Timestamp, thread, log level, logger name, and message

